It is probably not your fault but perhaps you can help out... Using the Distriqt NativeMaps ANE for iOS there exists a problem where Starling seems to fall asleep and does not wake up again, as soon as the map is being destroyed. The following exception is thrown:

[trace] IDS_CONSOLE_SANDBOX
[trace] IDS_CONSOLE_SECURITY_CONTEXT
[trace] Uncaught error 0 ArgumentError: Error #3672: Buffer creation failed. Internal error.
[Fault] exception, information=ArgumentError: Error #3672: Buffer creation failed. Internal error.

Distriqt provides a fix to this problem, with the following function that has to be called when the map is being destroyed:

``` as3
protected function resetStarling():void {
    var f:Function = function (step:int):void {
        var s:Starling = Starling.current;
        try {
            const viewport:Rectangle = s.viewPort;
            s.stage.stageWidth = viewport.width = s.nativeStage.stageWidth * (step == 0 ? 0.99 : 1);
            s.stage.stageHeight = viewport.height = s.nativeStage.stageHeight * (step == 0 ? 0.99 : 1);
            s.viewPort = viewport;
            } catch (e:Error) {
                trace(e.getStackTrace());
            }
        };
        setTimeout(function ():void {
            f.call(this, 0);
            setTimeout(function ():void {
                f.call(this, 1);
                }, 50);
            }, 50);
    }
```

There is still an exception being thrown but afterwards Starling at least runs without a problem:

[Fault] exception, information=Error: Error #3710: Requested Stage3D Operation failed to complete.
[trace] IDS_CONSOLE_SANDBOX
[trace] IDS_CONSOLE_SECURITY_CONTEXT
[trace] Uncaught error 0 Error: Error #3710: Requested Stage3D Operation failed to complete.

Any ideas what could cause such behavior?
